{
  "text": "But, nutritional status of study participants according to BMI classification had no significant association on maternal educational status, household asset (radio) ownership, family size, maternal age, number of meals per day, number of parity, farm animal ownership and residence of the lactating mothers. This was in contrary to the study conducted on women's nutritional status which had significant association on marital status, household assets, age of women and maternal education [CITATION_1] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "70899734"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "70899734": {
      "title": "Level and determinants of malnutrition in adolescent and adult women in Southern Ethiopia",
      "abstract": "The purpose of the study is to assess the levels and socioeconomic differentials in nutritional status of reproductive age women and to analyze their determinants. The paper uses the first large data set on womens nutritional status in Ethiopia collected on nearly 2400 women 15-49 years of age in urban and rural parts of five densely populated zones of southern Ethiopia. Findings show that around 40% of the women were malnourished with 21% moderately and severely deprived. Levels were almost 2 c times higher in rural areas and even higher among rural adolescents. The study identified household economic status womens age and marital status as important factors in explaining the variation in womens age and marital status as important factors in explaining the variation in womens nutritional status in both rural and urban areas. In urban areas the divorced and separated were much more likely to be under-nourished. In rural areas a womans higher education and economic status did though lessen the effects on malnutrition. Additionally administrative zone of residence was important in rural areas. There was also a significant relationship between a mothers and her childs acute wasting status. The sheer magnitude of these levels implies a silent but alarming epidemic of food and health deprivation. The links among poverty food insecurity diseases and womens and child malnutrition can have dire consequences for the future of human resource development policies of Ethiopia. Thus malnutrition must be addressed in adolescence taking the life cycle approach before the vicious cycle is repeated in children. (authors)"
    }
  }
}